    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
      <body> 
        <div rend="parallel">
            <p xml:id="Aink411-kilavi">
                paruvam kuṟittup pirinta talaimakaṉ apparuvattiṟku muṉṉē vantu talaiviyoṭu kūṭic cellā niṉṟuḻip paruvam vantatākat tāṉ paruvattiṟku muṉṉē vantamai tōṉṟak kūṟuvāṉ talaivikku uraittatu.            </p>
            <p xml:lang="en">
The hero who had separated after indicating the season [of his return], having returned before that season and having united with the heroine, as the season came when he was going, speaking so it became evident that he had come before the season, told [this] to the heroine.            </p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
                <lg xml:id="Aink411">
                    <l>ārkura leḻili yaḻituḷi citaṟik</l>
                    <l>kārtoṭaṅ kiṉṟāṟ kāmar puṟavē</l>
                    <l>vīḻtaru putuppuṉa lāṭukan</l>
                    <l>tāḻiruṅ kūntal vammati viraintē.</l>
          </lg>
          <lg xml:lang="en">
            <l>Scattering ruinous raindrops and with roaing loud clouds,</l>
            <l>the rainy season did begin. In the lovely woodland,</l>
            <l>we shall play in the new floods that bring desire.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot"><q xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi>vīḻ taru</hi></q>, here understood as relative clause meaning 'that bring desire', can equally well be translated as 'that descend'. In that case, <foreign xml:lang="ta-Latn">taru-tal</foreign> would function as an auxilliary verb, signifying an action outside of the control of the speaker. I see no particular reason to choose one interpretation over the other.</note></l> 
            <l>O one with the dark hanging tresses, come quickly!</l>
          </lg>
        </div>
      </body>
    </text>
